independent continuant
Value: A continuant that is a bearer of quality and realizable entity entities, in which other entities inhere and which itself cannot inhere in anything.@en

Subject: independent continuant
Value: b is an independent continuant = Def. b is a continuant which is such that there is no c and no t such that b s-depends_on c at t. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [017-002])@en

Subject: specifically dependent continuant
Value: A continuant that inheres in or is borne by other entities. Every instance of A requires some specific instance of B which must always be the same.@en

Subject: specifically dependent continuant
Value: b is a specifically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant & there is some independent continuant c which is not a spatial region and which is such that b s-depends_on c at every time t during the course of b’s existence. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [050-003])@en

Subject: food
Value: A physiological role played by any substance of either plant, animal or artificial origin which contains essential body nutrients that can be ingested by an organism to provide energy, promote growth, and maintain the processes of life.

Subject: food
Value: Any material that can be ingested by an organism.

Subject: food component
Value: A physiological role played by any substance that is distributed in foodstuffs. It includes materials derived from plants or animals, such as vitamins or minerals, as well as environmental contaminants.

Subject: food component
Value: Any substance that is distributed in foodstuffs. It includes materials derived from plants or animals, such as vitamins or minerals, as well as environmental contaminants.

Subject: cell activation

Subject: cell activation

Subject: cellular_component
Value: A location, relative to cellular compartments and structures, occupied by a macromolecular machine when it carries out a molecular function. There are two ways in which the gene ontology describes locations of gene products: (1) relative to cellular structures (e.g., cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane) or compartments (e.g., mitochondrion), and (2) the stable macromolecular complexes of which they are parts (e.g., the ribosome).

Subject: cellular_component
Value: The part of a cell or its extracellular environment in which a gene product is located. A gene product may be located in one or more parts of a cell and its location may be as specific as a particular macromolecular complex, that is, a stable, persistent association of macromolecules that function together.

Subject: amino acid metabolic process
Value: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids, carboxylic acids containing one or more amino groups, as carried out by individual cells.

Subject: amino acid metabolic process

Subject: transport
Value: The directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) or cellular components (such as complexes and organelles) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or a transporter complex, a pore or a motor protein.

Subject: transport
Value: The directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) or cellular components (such as complexes and organelles) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter, pore or motor protein.

Subject: microtubule-based movement
Value: A microtubule-based process that results in the movement of organelles, other microtubules, or other cellular components.  Examples include motor-driven movement along microtubules and movement driven by polymerization or depolymerization of microtubules.

Subject: microtubule-based movement
Value: A microtubule-based process that results in the movement of organelles, other microtubules, or other cellular components. Examples include motor-driven movement along microtubules and movement driven by polymerization or depolymerization of microtubules.

Subject: cell-cell signaling
Value: Any process that mediates the transfer of information from one cell to another. This process includes signal transduction in the receiving cell and, where applicable, release of a ligand and any processes that actively facilitate its transport and presentation to the receiving cell.  Examples include signaling via soluble ligands, via cell adhesion molecules and via gap junctions.

Subject: cell-cell signaling
Value: Any process that mediates the transfer of information from one cell to another. This process includes signal transduction in the receiving cell and, where applicable, release of a ligand and any processes that actively facilitate its transport and presentation to the receiving cell. Examples include signaling via soluble ligands, via cell adhesion molecules and via gap junctions.

Subject: membrane

Subject: sexual reproduction
Value: A reproduction process that creates a new organism by combining the genetic material of two gametes, which may come from two organisms or from a single organism, in the case of self-fertilizing hermaphrodites, e.g. C. elegans, or self-fertilization in plants. It occurs both in eukaryotes and prokaryotes: in multicellular eukaryotic organisms, an individual is created anew; in prokaryotes, the initial cell has additional or transformed genetic material. In a process called genetic recombination, genetic material (DNA) originating from two gametes join up so that homologous sequences are aligned with each other, and this is followed by exchange of genetic information. After the new recombinant chromosome is formed, it is passed on to progeny.

Subject: sexual reproduction
Value: A type of reproduction that combines the genetic material of two gametes (such as a sperm or egg cell or fungal spores). The gametes have an haploid genome (with a single set of chromosomes, the product of a meiotic division) and combines with one another to produce a zygote (diploid).

Subject: definition
Value:
2012-04-05: 
Barry Smith

The official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions'  is terrible.

Can you fix to something like:

A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.

Alan Ruttenberg

Your proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. 

On the specifics of the proposed definition:

We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. 

Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. 

We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with.  @en

Subject: contained in
Value:
Intended meaning:
domain: material entity
range: spatial region or site (immaterial continuant)
        @en

Subject: spatially disjoint from
Value: There are two ways to encode this as a shortcut relation. The other possibility to use an annotation assertion between two classes, and expand this to a disjointness axiom. @en

Subject: capable of
Value: A relation between a material entity (such as a cell) and a process, in which the material entity has the ability to carry out the process.

Subject: results in maturation of
Value: an annotation of gene X to cell maturation with results_in_maturation_of CL:0000057 (fibroblast) means that the fibroblast is mature at the end of the process

Subject: results in transport along
Value: Holds between p and l when p is a transportation or localization process and the outcome of this process is to move c from one location to another, and the route taken by c follows a path that is aligned_with l

Subject: disposition
Value: b is a disposition means: b is a realizable entity & b’s bearer is some material entity & b is such that if it ceases to exist, then its bearer is physically changed, & b’s realization occurs when and because this bearer is in some special physical circumstances, & this realization occurs in virtue of the bearer’s physical make-up. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [062-002])@en

Subject: specifically dependent continuant
Value: b is a specifically dependent continuant = Def. b is a continuant & there is some independent continuant c which is not a spatial region and which is such that b s-depends_on c at every time t during the course of b’s existence. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [050-003])@en

Subject: role
Value: b is a role means: b is a realizable entity & b exists because there is some single bearer that is in some special physical, social, or institutional set of circumstances in which this bearer does not have to be& b is not such that, if it ceases to exist, then the physical make-up of the bearer is thereby changed. (axiom label in BFO2 Reference: [061-001])@en

Subject: preceded_by
Value: x is preceded by y if and only if the time point at which y ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which x starts. Formally: x preceded by y iff ω(y) <= α(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: precedes
Value: x precedes y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x precedes y iff ω(x) <= α(y), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.@en

Subject: occurs in
Value: b occurs_in c =def b is a process and c is a material entity or immaterial entity& there exists a spatiotemporal region r and b occupies_spatiotemporal_region r.& forall(t) if b exists_at t then c exists_at t & there exist spatial regions s and s’ where & b spatially_projects_onto s at t& c is occupies_spatial_region s’ at t& s is a proper_continuant_part_of s’ at t@en

Value: [copied from inverse property 'occurs in'] b occurs_in c =def b is a process and c is a material entity or immaterial entity& there exists a spatiotemporal region r and b occupies_spatiotemporal_region r.& forall(t) if b exists_at t then c exists_at t & there exist spatial regions s and s’ where & b spatially_projects_onto s at t& c is occupies_spatial_region s’ at t& s is a proper_continuant_part_of s’ at t@en

Subject: anterior_to
Value: x anterior to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the head. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that extends through an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail.

Subject: anterior_to
Value: x anterior_to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the head. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that bisects an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail: bearer

Subject: distal_to
Value: x distal to y iff x is further along the proximo-distal axis than y, towards the appendage tip. A proximo-distal axis extends from tip of an appendage (distal) to where it joins the body (proximal).

Subject: distal_to
Value: x distal_to y iff x is further along the proximo-distal axis than y, towards the appendage tip. A proximo-distal axis extends from tip of an appendage (distal) to where it joins the body (proximal).

Subject: dorsal_to
Value: x dorsal to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the back. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that extends through an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: dorsal_to
Value: x dorsal_to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the back. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that bisects an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: posterior to
Value: x posterior to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the body/tail. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that extends through an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail.

Subject: posterior to
Value: x posterior_to y iff x is further along the antero-posterior axis than y, towards the body/tail. An antero-posterior axis is an axis that bisects an organism from head end to opposite end of body or tail.

Subject: proximal_to
Value: x proximal to y iff x is closer to the point of attachment with the body than y.

Subject: proximal_to
Value: x proximal_to y iff x is closer to the point of attachment with the body than y.

Subject: ventral_to
Value: x ventral to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the front. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that extends through an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: ventral_to
Value: x ventral_to y iff x is further along the dorso-ventral axis than y, towards the front. A dorso-ventral axis is an axis that bisects an organism from back (e.g. spinal column) to front (e.g. belly).

Subject: in_proximal_side_of
Value: x in proximal side of y <=> if y is subdivided into two proximal and distal portions, y is part of the proximal portion.

Subject: in distal side of
Value: x in distal side of y <=> if y is subdivided into two proximal and distal portions, y is part of the distal portion.

Subject: parallel to
Value: x is parallel t y iff x and y are lines or planes which when extended indefinitely do not cross.

Subject: immediately deep to
Value: x immediately deep to y iff x deep_to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: immediately superficial to
Value: x immediately superficial to y iff x superficial to y and x is contiguous with y.

Subject: lipid
Value: 'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.

Subject: cyclic nucleotide-dependent protein kinase activity
Value: cNMP-dependent catalysis of the reaction: ATP + a protein = ADP + a phosphoprotein.

Subject: cAMP-dependent protein kinase activity
Value: cAMP-dependent catalysis of the reaction: ATP + a protein = ADP + a phosphoprotein.

Subject: behavior process
Value: \"The action, reaction, or performance of an organism in response to external or internal stimuli.\" [GO:GO\:0007610]

Subject: kinesthetic behavior
Value: \"Movement behavior of the body or its parts.\"

Subject: regulation of behavior
Value: \"Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of behavior, the specific actions or reactions of an organism in response to external or internal stimuli.\" [GO:0050795]

Subject: stability
Value: quality, state, or degree of being stable.

Subject: characteristic of
Value: a relation between a specifically dependent continuant (the characteristic) and any other entity (the bearer), in which the characteristic depends on the bearer for its existence.@en

Subject: characteristic of
Value: a relation between a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent) and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: bearer of
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a specifically dependent continuant (the dependent), in which the dependent specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: participates in
Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: has participant
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: function of
Value: a relation between a function and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: quality of
Value: a relation between a quality and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: role of
Value: a relation between a role and an independent continuant (the bearer), in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has function
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a function, in which the function specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has quality
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a quality, in which the quality specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has role
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a role, in which the role specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: has disposition
Value: a relation between an independent continuant (the bearer) and a disposition, in which the disposition specifically depends on the bearer for its existence@en

Subject: location of
Value: a relation between two independent continuants, the location and the target, in which the target is entirely within the location@en

Subject: located in
Value: a relation between two independent continuants, the target and the location, in which the target is entirely within the location@en

Subject: 2D boundary of
Value: a relation between a 2D immaterial entity (the boundary) and a material entity, in which the boundary delimits the material entity@en

Subject: has 2D boundary
Value: a relation between a material entity and a 2D immaterial entity (the boundary), in which the boundary delimits the material entity@en

Subject: has component process
Value: w 'has process component' p if p and w are processes,  w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y if and only if there exists some z such that x has part z and z part of y

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y iff they have some part in common.

Subject: only in taxon
Value: x only in taxon y if and only if x is in taxon y, and there is no other organism z such that y!=z a and x is in taxon z.

Subject: in taxon
Value: x is in taxon y if an only if y is an organism, and the relationship between x and y is one of: part of (reflexive), developmentally preceded by, derives from, secreted by, expressed.

Subject: connected to
Value: a is connected to b if and only if a and b are discrete structure, and there exists some connecting structure c, such that c connects a and b

Subject: connects
Value: c connects a if and only if there exist some b such that a and b are similar parts of the same system, and c connects b, specifically, c connects a with b. When one structure connects two others it unites some aspect of the function or role they play within the system.

Subject: attached to part of
Value: a is attached to part of b if a is attached to b, or a is attached to some p, where p is part of b.

Subject: has component
Value: w 'has component' p if w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: develops from
Value: x develops from y if and only if either (a) x directly develops from y or (b) there exists some z such that x directly develops from z and z develops from y

Subject: regulates
Value: p regulates q iff p is causally upstream of q, the execution of p is not constant and varies according to specific conditions, and p influences the rate or magnitude of execution of q due to an effect either on some enabler of q or some enabler of a part of q.

Subject: regulates
Value: process(P1) regulates process(P2) iff: P1 results in the initiation or termination of P2 OR affects the frequency of its initiation or termination OR affects the magnitude or rate of output of P2.

Subject: negatively regulates
Value: p negatively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p decreases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: positively regulates
Value: p positively regulates q iff p regulates q, and p increases the rate or magnitude of execution of q.

Subject: capable of part of
Value: c stands in this relationship to p if and only if there exists some p' such that c is capable_of p', and p' is part_of p.

Subject: surrounded by
Value: x surrounded_by y if and only if (1) x is adjacent to y and for every region r that is adjacent to x, r overlaps y (2) the shared boundary between x and y occupies the majority of the outermost boundary of x

Subject: surrounded by
Value: x surrounded_by y iff: x is adjacent to y and for every region r adjacent to x, r overlaps y

Subject: adjacent to
Value: x adjacent to y if and only if x and y share a boundary.

Subject: adjacent to
Value: x adjacent_to y iff: x and y share a boundary

Subject: starts with
Value: x starts with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: α(y) = α(x) ∧ ω(y) < ω(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.

Subject: develops from part of
Value: x develops from part of y if and only if there exists some z such that x develops from z and z is part of y

Subject: develops in
Value: x develops_in y if x is located in y whilst x is developing

Subject: ends with
Value: x ends with y if and only if x has part y and the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: α(y) > α(x) ∧ ω(y) = ω(x), where α is a function that maps a process to a start point, and ω is a function that maps a process to an end point.

Subject: has start location
Value: x 'has starts location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'starts with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has end location
Value: x 'has end location' y if and only if there exists some process z such that x 'ends with' z and z 'occurs in' y

Subject: has input
Value: p has input c iff: p is a process, c is a material entity, c is a participant in p, c is present at the start of p, and the state of c is modified during p.

Subject: has output
Value: p has output c iff c is a participant in p, c is present at the end of p, and c is not present in the same state at the beginning of p.

Subject: has developmental contribution from
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y@en

Subject: has developmental contribution from
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y.

Subject: developmentally contributes to
Value: inverse of has developmental contribution from

Subject: developmentally induced by
Value: t1 developmentally_induced_by t2 if there is a process of organ induction (GO:0001759) with t1 and t2 as interacting participants. t2 causes t1 to change its fate from a precursor tissue type T to T', where T' develops_from T.

Subject: developmentally induced by
Value: t1 induced_by t2 if there is a process of developmental induction (GO:0031128) with t1 and t2 as interacting participants. t2 causes t1 to change its fate from a precursor anatomical structure type T to T', where T' develops_from T

Subject: acts upstream of
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: developmentally replaces
Value: x developmentally replaces y if and only if there is some developmental process that causes x to move or to cease to exist, and for the site that was occupied by x to become occupied by y, where y either comes into existence in this site or moves to this site from somewhere else

Subject: results in developmental progression of
Value: p results in the developmental progression of s iff p is a developmental process and s is an anatomical structure and p causes s to undergo a change in state at some point along its natural developmental cycle (this cycle starts with its formation, through the mature structure, and ends with its loss).

Subject: results in development of
Value: p 'results in development of' c if and only if p is a developmental process and p results in the state of c changing from its initial state as a primordium or anlage through its mature state and to its final state.

Subject: causally upstream of, positive effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, positive effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p is required for the execution of q.

Subject: causally upstream of, negative effect
Value: p is causally upstream of, negative effect q iff p is casually upstream of q, and the execution of p decreases the execution of q.

Subject: characteristic of part of
Value: q characteristic of part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: characteristic of part of
Value: q inheres in part of w if and only if there exists some p such that q inheres in p and p part of w.

Subject: enables
Value: c enables p iff c is capable of p and c acts to execute p.

Subject: part of structure that is capable of
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: involved in
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: regulates levels of
Value: p regulates levels of c if p regulates some amount (PATO:0000070) of c

Subject: member of
Value: is member of is a mereological relation between a item and a collection.

Subject: has member
Value: has member is a mereological relation between a collection and an item.

Subject: attached to
Value: a is attached to b if and only if a and b are discrete objects or object parts, and there are physical connections between a and b such that a force pulling a will move b, or a force pulling b will move a

Subject: has muscle origin
Value: m has_muscle_origin s iff m is attached_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s does not move. The site of the origin tends to be more proximal and have greater mass than what the other end attaches to.@en

Subject: has muscle insertion
Value: m has_muscle_insertion s iff m is attaches_to s, and it is the case that when m contracts, s moves. Insertions are usually connections of muscle via tendon to bone.@en

Subject: tributary of
Value: x tributary_of y if and only if x a channel for the flow of a substance into y, where y is larger than x. If x and y are hydrographic features, then y is the main stem of a river, or a lake or bay, but not the sea or ocean. If x and y are anatomical, then y is a vein.

Subject: spatially coextensive with
Value: x spatially_coextensive_with y if and inly if x and y have the same location

Subject: branching part of
Value: x is a branching part of y if and only if x is part of y and x is connected directly or indirectly to the main stem of y

Subject: has developmental potential involving
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally induce
Value: x has potential to developmentally induce y iff x developmentally induces y or x is capable of developmentally inducing y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: indirectly positively regulates
Value: p indirectly positively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p positively regulates q.

Subject: indirectly negatively regulates
Value: p indirectly negatively regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: causally related to
Value: relation that links two events, processes, states, or objects such that one event, process, state, or object (a cause) contributes to the production of another event, process, state, or object (an effect) where the cause is partly or wholly responsible for the effect, and the effect is partly or wholly dependent on the cause.

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q if and only if p precedes q and p and q are linked in a causal chain

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q iff p is causally related to q, the end of p precedes the end of q, and p is not an occurrent part of q.

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff both (a) p immediately precedes q and (b) p is causally upstream of q. In addition, the output of p  must be an input of q.

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q, and the end of p is coincident with the beginning of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p 'causally upstream or within' q iff (1) the end of p is before the end of q and (2) the execution of p exerts some causal influence over the outputs of q; i.e. if p was abolished or the outputs of p were to be modified, this would necessarily affect q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p is 'causally upstream or within' q iff p is causally related to q, and the end of p precedes, or is coincident with, the end of q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: contributes to morphology of
Value: p contributes to morphology of w if and only if a change in the morphology of p entails a change in the morphology of w. Examples: every skull contributes to morphology of the head which it is a part of. Counter-example: nuclei do not generally contribute to the morphology of the cell they are part of, as they are buffered by cytoplasm.

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y if and only if more than half of the mass of x is made from y or units of the same type as y.

Subject: composed primarily of
Value: x composed_primarily_of y iff: more than half of the mass of x is made from parts of y

Subject: has part that occurs in
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: existence starts during
Value: x existence starts during y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts and before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y).

Subject: existence starts with
Value: x starts ends with y if and only if the time point at which x starts is equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts with y iff α(x) = α(y).

Subject: existence overlaps
Value: x existence overlaps y if and only if either (a) the start of x is part of y or (b) the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff (α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y)) OR (ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y))

Subject: existence starts and ends during
Value: x exists during y if and only if: 1) the time point at which x begins to exist is after or equal to the time point at which y begins and 2) the time point at which x ceases to exist is before or equal to the point at which y ends. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y)

Subject: existence ends during
Value: x existence ends during y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends and after or equivalent to the point at which y starts. Formally: x existence ends during y iff ω(x) <= ω(y) and ω(x) >= α(y).

Subject: existence ends with
Value: x existence ends with y if and only if the time point at which x ends is equivalent to the time point at which y ends. Formally: x existence ends with y iff ω(x) = ω(y).

Subject: transformation of
Value: x transformation of y if x is the immediate transformation of y, or is linked to y through a chain of transformation relationships

Subject: immediate transformation of
Value: x immediate transformation of y iff x immediately succeeds y temporally at a time boundary t, and all of the matter present in x at t is present in y at t, and all the matter in y at t is present in x at t

Subject: existence starts during or after
Value: c existence starts during s iff start_of(c) part_of s.

Subject: existence starts during or after
Value: x existence starts during or after y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts during or after y iff α (x) >= α (y).

Subject: end stage
Value: c existence ends during s iff  end_of(c) part_of s.

Subject: end stage
Value: x existence ends during or before y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one of direct activation or direct inhibition. p may be upstream, downstream, part of or a container of q.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one where the execution of p influences the execution of q. p may be upstream, downstream, part of, or a container of q.

Subject: towards
Value: q towards e2 if and only if q is a relational quality such that q inheres-in some e, and e != e2 and q is dependent on e2

Subject: has muscle antagonist
Value: m1 has_muscle_antagonist m2 iff m1 has_muscle_insertion s, m2 has_muscle_insection s, m1 acts in opposition to m2, and m2 is responsible for returning the structure to its initial position.

Subject: lumen of
Value: x lumen_of y iff x is the space or substance that is part of y and does not cross any of the inner membranes or boundaries of y that is maximal with respect to the volume of the convex hull.

Subject: luminal space of
Value: s is luminal space of x iff s is lumen_of x and s is an immaterial entity

Subject: directly regulates
Value: p directly regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: results in breakdown of
Value: p results in breakdown of c if and only if the execution of p leads to c no longer being present at the end of p

Subject: results in organization of
Value: p results in organization of c iff p results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of c

Subject: directly positively regulates
Value: p directly positively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p positively regulates q.

Subject: directly negatively regulates
Value: p directly negatively regulates q iff p is immediately causally upstream of q, and p negatively regulates q.

Subject: produces
Value: a produces b if some process that occurs_in a has_output b, where a and b are material entities. Examples: hybridoma cell line produces monoclonal antibody reagent; chondroblast produces avascular GAG-rich matrix.

Subject: produced by
Value: a produced_by b iff some process that occurs_in b has_output a.

Subject: has primary input or output
Value: p 'has primary input ot output' c iff either (a) p 'has primary input' c or (b) p 'has primary output' c.

Subject: has primary output
Value: p has primary output c if (a) p has output c and (b) the goal of process is to modify, produce, or transform c.

Subject: has primary input
Value: p has primary input c if (a) p has input c and (b) the goal of process is to modify, consume, or transform c.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: acts on population of
Value: p acts on population of c iff c' is a collection, has members of type c, and p has participant c

Subject: indirectly causally upstream of
Value: p is indirectly causally upstream of q iff p is causally upstream of q and there exists some process r such that p is causally upstream of r and r is causally upstream of q.

Subject: indirectly regulates
Value: p indirectly regulates q iff p is indirectly causally upstream of q and p regulates q.

Subject: different in magnitude relative to
Value: q1 different_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) NOT =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: increased in magnitude relative to
Value: q1 increased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) > magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: decreased in magnitude relative to
Value: q1 decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) < magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: has cross section
Value: s3 has_cross_section s3 if and only if : there exists some 2d plane that intersects the bearer of s3, and the impression of s3 upon that plane has shape quality s2.

Subject: reciprocal of
Value: q1 reciprocal_of q2 if and only if : q1 and q2 are relational qualities and a phenotype e q1 e2 mutually implies a phenotype e2 q2 e.

Subject: results in changes to anatomical or cellular structure
Value: p has anatomical participant c iff p has participant c, and c is an anatomical entity

Subject: anteriorly connected to
Value: x anteriorly_connected_to y iff the anterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x posterior_to y.

Subject: conduit for
Value: x is a conduit for y iff y passes through the lumen of x.

Subject: distally connected to
Value: x distally_connected_to y iff the distal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x proximal_to y.

Subject: indirectly_supplies
Value: a indirectly_supplies s iff a has a branch and the branch supplies or indirectly supplies s.

Subject: posteriorly connected to
Value: x posteriorly_connected_to y iff the posterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x anterior_to y.

Subject: proximally connected to
Value: x proximally_connected_to y iff the proximal part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x distal_to y.

Subject: site_of
Value: c site_of p if c is the bearer of a disposition that is realized by a process that has p as part.

obsolete symmetric radial glial cell division in forebrain increased occurrence, abnormal
